    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A confidentiality period is the time frame during which a party must keep secrets, while a survival clause ensures that certain contract terms, like confidentiality, remain in effect even after the agreement ends. Think of it like a contract that has a main body and then a few extra limbs that stay attached long after the rest of the body has been laid to rest.\n\nIn a standard contract, the confidentiality period is usually defined by a specific duration, such as \"for two years after termination.\" However, a survival clause is the legal mechanism that explicitly states which parts of the contract survive the expiration of the entire agreement. Without a survival clause, you might assume that once the contract expires, all obligations vanish, but the survival clause is the one that tells you, \"No, the confidentiality obligation stays alive forever (or for a set time) even though the rest of the deal is over.\"\n\nIt's a bit like a goblin who was supposed to be the last one in the room; the contract says everyone else leaves, but the goblin is the only one who stays. If you don't have a survival clause, the goblin might leave too, and you'd be left with no protection. But if you do have it, the goblin",
      "source": "target",
